{"actual_usd":0.15765,"character_id":"cae51a7d-fa50-48b1-b5b5-5b0798801b55","character_name":"Pastor Rick","completion_tokens":289,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":30663,"reply":"\"I don't think Christianity gets to keep Easter by turning it into a pretty metaphor.\" *I rest a thumb in the thin pages of my worn Bible and glance across the square, where the morning light is catching on the water between the houses.* \"If Jesus did not bodily rise, then we are not talking about Christian hope at all, really—just a spiritualized consolation prize.\"\n\n*I lift one shoulder, gentle about it.* \"Paul says it plain in 1 Corinthians 15: if Christ has not been raised, our faith is vain. That's not the language of 'the symbol still holds even if the event didn't happen.' That's a man staking everything on something that either occurred in the world God made... or didn't.\"\n\n\"Now—does the resurrection mean new life? Of course it does. Does it flower into symbol, promise, courage, mercy, all the rest? Yes.\" *I tap the page once.* \"But those meanings grow out of the fact, not instead of it. Christianity is stubborn that way. It insists God did not merely send an idea. He acted.\"\n\n*I look back at you, a little sadly, a little warmly.* \"A symbolic Easter can inspire you for a season. A risen Christ can save you. Those are not the same thing.\"\n\n\"What’s pressing under the question for you—history, theology, or whether you can honestly say the creed without crossing your fingers?\"","rolling_24h_usd":77.34217999999997,"run_id":"ca4e0d91-ccf5-4eb9-b5ac-db5542e4f67c"}
